{{Infobox book | name = The Rational Optimist | author = Matt Ridley | image = The_Rational_Optimist.jpg | caption = How Prosperity Evolves | country = United States | language = English | publisher = Harper | release_date = 18 May 2010 | media_type = Print (Hardcover) | pages = 448 }}
'''''The Rational Optimist''''' is a 2010 [[popular science]] book by [[Matt Ridley]], author of ''[[The Red Queen: Sex and the Evolution of Human Nature]]''. The book primarily focuses on the benefits of the innate human tendency to trade goods and services. Ridley argues that this trait, together with the specialization linked to it, is the source of modern human civilization, and that, as people increasingly specialize in their skill sets, we will have increased trade and more prosperity.<ref>{{cite web|title=Getting better all the time|url=http://www.economist.com/node/16103826|date=13 May 2010|work=The Economist}}</ref>
==Reception== [[Bill Gates]] praised the book for critiquing opposition to international aid, but criticised the book for under-representing [[global catastrophic risk]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gatesnotes.com/Books/Africa-Needs-Aid-Not-Flawed-Theories|title=The Rational Optimist: How Prosperity Evolves|author=Bill Gates|date=30 Nov 2010}}</ref> [[Ricardo Salinas Pliego]] praised the book as a defence of free trade and globalisation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/ricardo-b-salinas/the-rational-optimist_b_1872247.html|title='The Rational Optimist': Review|author=Ricardo B. Salinas|date=9 Dec 2012|work=Huffington Post}}</ref> [[Michael Shermer]] gave the book positive reviews in ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]''<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v465/n7296/full/465294a.html|title=Science, freedom and trade|work=Nature|volume=265|date=20 May 2010|doi=10.1038/465294a|author=Michael Shermer|pages=294–295}}</ref> and ''[[Scientific American]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/when-ideas-have-sex/|title=When Ideas Have Sex|date=1 May 2010|author=Michael Shermer}}</ref> before going on to present similar ideas in conference talks, and writing ''[[The Moral Arc]]'' partly in response. [[David Papineau]] praised the book for refuting "doomsayers who insist that everything is going from bad to worse".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2010/jun/13/the-rational-optimist-matt-ridley|title=The Rational Optimist: How Prosperity Evolves by Matt Ridley|author=David Papineau|date=13 June 2010|work=The Observer}}</ref>
[[George Monbiot]] criticised the book in his [[The Guardian|''Guardian'']] column. <ref>{{cite web|title=Matt Ridley's Rational Optimist is telling the rich what they want to hear|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/cif-green/2010/jun/18/matt-ridley-rational-optimist-errors|author=George Monbiot|work=The Guardian}}</ref> Critics of the book say it fails to address wealth inequality, and other criticisms of globalization.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/13/books/review/Easterly-t.html?pagewanted=all|title=A High-Five for the Invisible Hand|author=William Easterly|date=11 June 2010|work=New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/bookreviews/7817914/The-Rational-Optimist-How-Prosperity-Evolves-by-Matt-Ridley-review.html|title=The Rational Optimist: How Prosperity Evolves by Matt Ridley: review|first=Robert|last=Colvile|date=14 June 2010|publisher=|accessdate=27 July 2018|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/reviews/the-rational-optimist-by-matt-ridleybr-pandoras-seed-by-spencer-wells-1996793.html|title=The Rational Optimist, By Matt RidleyPandora's Seed, By Spencer|publisher=|accessdate=27 July 2018}}</ref>
==See also== * ''[[The Moral Arc]]'' * ''[[The Better Angels of Our Nature]]''
